<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="mainText">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Synotaxidae" genus="Synotaxus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synotaxus</taxonomicName>
Simon Figures 295-298
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="mainText">Carapace slightly flattened, eyes overhanging clypeus. Chelicerae small, probably with one or two teeth on the anterior margin. none posterior. Legs very long, first femur 1.5 times length of body. Abdomen with a long extension beyond spinnerets (Fig. 295). Colulus large. Uniformly white in color]</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="mainText">Palpus with paracymbium absent; median apophysis very small; conductor may be absent. Haematodocha may attach bulb to dorsum of alveolus of eymbium rather than to proximal end. Palpal patella of male has a spur (Fig. 298).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="mainText">
Separated from 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Argyrodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Argyrodes</taxonomicName>
by palpal patellar spur, and by unmodified eye region of male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="mainText">Only four species known, from South America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
